'''Curtis Michael Casali''' (born November 9, 1988) is an American [[professional baseball]] [[catcher]] for the [[Cincinnati Reds]] of [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB). He made his MLB debut in 2014 with the [[Tampa Bay Rays]].

==Amateur career==
Casali was born in [[Walnut Creek, California]], but raised in [[New Canaan, Connecticut]]. Casali attended [[New Canaan High School]], where he also starred in [[basketball]], and [[American football|football]] as a [[quarterback]], leading the team to a state championship. Casali earned first-team All-State honors in football and baseball, and was named the second best prospect from Connecticut/Rhode Island in the June 2007 draft.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vucommodores.com/sports/m-basebl/mtt/curt_casali_323231.html|title=Curt Casali Bio - Vanderbilt Official Athletic Site|publisher=|accessdate=April 24, 2016}}</ref>

[[File:IMG 0022 Curt Casali.jpg|left|upright|thumb|Casali batting for the [[Lakeland Flying Tigers]] in 2012]]
Casali played [[college baseball]] at [[Vanderbilt University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stamfordadvocate.com/baseball/article/New-Canaan-s-Curt-Casali-finds-success-with-544586.php|title=New Canaan's Curt Casali finds success with Vanderbilt baseball|work=StamfordAdvocate|accessdate=April 24, 2016}}</ref> During his four years at Vanderbilt, he had a .316 [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]], a .430 [[on-base percentage]], a .502 [[slugging percentage]], 27 [[home runs]], and 167 runs batted in (RBI). Casali made it to the College World Series finals in 2011 with Vanderbilt, but was eliminated by Florida in double elimination play.
==Professional career==
===Tampa Bay Rays===
The [[Detroit Tigers]] selected Casali in the 10th round of the [[2011 Major League Baseball draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://weston-ct.patch.com/groups/sports/p/new-canaans-casali-drafted-by-detroit-tigers-2|title=New Canaan's Casali Drafted by Detroit Tigers|first=Paul|last=Devlin|date=June 8, 2011|work=Weston-Redding-Easton, CT Patch|accessdate=April 24, 2016}}</ref> He made his professional debut that season for the [[Connecticut Tigers]]. On March 25, 2013, the Tigers traded Casali to the [[Tampa Bay Rays]] for [[Kyle Lobstein]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tampabay.rays.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20130325&content_id=43282068&vkey=pr_tb&c_id=tb|title=Rays acquire catcher Curt Casali from Tigers|work=Tampa Bay Rays|accessdate=April 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncadvertiser.com/20604/detroit-trades-casali-to-tampa-bay-rays/|title=Detroit trades Casali to Tampa Bay Rays|work=New Canaan Advertiser|accessdate=April 24, 2016}}</ref> The Rays assigned him to the [[Charlotte Stone Crabs]] and then promoted him to the [[Montgomery Biscuits]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newcanaannewsonline.com/news/article/New-Canaan-s-Casali-promoted-to-Tampa-Bay-s-4689650.php|title=New Canaan's Casali promoted to Tampa Bay's Double-A squad; goes 3-for-3 in debut|work=New Canaan News|accessdate=April 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stamfordadvocate.com/sports/article/Casali-promoted-to-Double-A-Montgomery-Biscuits-4704176.php|title=Casali promoted to Double-A Montgomery Biscuits|work=StamfordAdvocate|accessdate=April 24, 2016}}</ref> In 35 games with Montgomery, Casali hit .383 with a .483 on-base percentage and .600 slugging percentage, with five home runs. Overall, he hit .317/.405/.489 and 10 home runs. In 2014, he was invited to [[spring training]] by the Rays.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newcanaan.dailyvoice.com/sports/tampa-bay-rays-invite-new-canaans-curt-casali-spring-training|title=Tampa Bay Rays Invite New Canaan's Curt Casali To Spring Training|work=New Canaan Daily Voice|accessdate=April 24, 2016}}</ref> He returned to Montgomery to start the 2014 season.<ref>[http://archive.montgomeryadvertiser.com/article/20140403/SPORTS01/304030027/Biscuits-Season-Opener-Set-another-go-round-Former-Vanderbilt-teammates-share-journey Biscuits Season Opener - Set for another go-round: Former Vanderbilt teammates share journey] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502013225/http://archive.montgomeryadvertiser.com/article/20140403/SPORTS01/304030027/Biscuits-Season-Opener-Set-another-go-round-Former-Vanderbilt-teammates-share-journey |date=May 2, 2014 }}</ref> He was promoted to the [[Durham Bulls]] in May.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncadvertiser.com/32682/curt-casali-moving-up-to-triple-a-durham-bulls/|title=Connecticut's Curt Casali moving up to Triple-A Durham Bulls|work=New Canaan Advertiser|accessdate=April 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newcanaan.dailyvoice.com/sports/new-canaans-casali-rides-hot-streak-closer-major-leagues|title=New Canaan's Casali Rides Hot Streak Closer To Major Leagues|work=New Canaan Daily Voice|accessdate=April 24, 2016}}</ref>

On July 18, 2014, Casali played his first major league game against the [[Minnesota Twins]]. He recorded a hit in his first at bat and a run later in the inning. On July 28, 2015 Casali hit two home runs in one game against the Detroit Tigers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newcanaanite.com/new-canaans-curt-casali-hits-two-home-runs-for-tampa-bay-rays-29937|title=New Canaan’s Curt Casali Hits Two Home Runs for Tampa Bay Rays|first=Terry|last=Dinan|date=July 27, 2015|work=NewCanaanite.com|accessdate=April 24, 2016}}</ref> One night later, Casali repeated the feat by hitting two homers against former teammate and fellow Vanderbilt alum [[David Price (baseball)|David Price]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newcanaanite.com/deja-vu-all-over-again-casali-homers-twice-for-second-consecutive-game-29989|title=‘Déjà Vu All Over Again’: Casali Homers Twice for Second Consecutive Game|first=Terry|last=Dinan|date=July 28, 2015|work=NewCanaanite.com|accessdate=April 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>Calcaterra, Craig [http://hardballtalk.nbcsports.com/2015/07/29/curt-casali-is-having-one-heck-of-a-week/ Curt Casali is having one heck of a week] ''NBC Sports''. July 29, 2015</ref>

Casali opened the 2016 season in a [[platoon system|platoon]] with [[Hank Conger]].<ref>[http://fantasy.usatoday.com/news/curt-casali-hank-conger-to-split-duties]</ref> Casali hit .169 before being optioned to the [[Durham Bulls]] on August 4, 2016. He was outrighted to Triple-A on November 6, 2017, and elected free agency later that day.

===Texas Rangers===
On November 28, 2017, the [[Los Angeles Angels]] signed Casali to a minor league contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlbtraderumors.com/2017/11/angels-agree-to-minor-league-deals-with-curt-casali-colin-walsh.html|title=Angels Agree To Minor League Deals With Curt Casali, Colin Walsh|last=Adams|first=Steve|work=mlbtraderumors.com|date=November 28, 2017|accessdate=November 28, 2017}}</ref> However, they released him on January 16, 2018. 

Tpwo days later he signed a minor league contract with the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]].<ref>[https://www.mlbtraderumors.com/2018/01/rangers-sign-curt-casali.html Rangers Sign Curt Casali]</ref> He was released on March 21, 2018.

===Second stint with Rays===
On March 21, 2018, Casali signed a minor league deal with the [[Tampa Bay Rays]].

===Cincinnati Reds===
On May 31, 2018, Casali was traded to the [[Cincinnati Reds]].<ref>{{cite web |title= Rays trade Curt Casali to Reds |url=http://www.tampabay.com/blogs/rays/2018/05/31/rays-trade-curt-casali-to-reds/ |publisher= Tampa Bay Times |accessdate= July 4, 2019}}</ref> In July he injured his right knee, and was expected to be sidelined for three to four weeks.

